{{Original research|date=February 2016}}
{{Infobox spaceflight|auto=all | name = Dong Fang Hong I | image = DFH-1 Satellite.jpg | image_caption = DFH-1 model
| mission_type = Technology | operator = [[China Academy of Space Technology|CAST]] | COSPAR_ID = 1970-034A | SATCAT = 4382 | mission_duration = 20&nbsp;days
| spacecraft_bus = | manufacturer = | dry_mass = | launch_mass = {{convert|173.0|kg|lb}}<ref name="NSSDC">{{cite web|url=http://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraftDisplay.do?id=1970-034A|title=PRC 1|publisher=National Space Science Data Center|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref> | power =
| launch_date = {{start-date|24 April 1970, 13:35:45|timezone=yes}}&nbsp;UTC<ref name="launchlog">{{cite web|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/launchlog.txt|title=Launch Log|first=Jonathan|last=McDowell|work=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref> | launch_rocket = [[Long March 1|Chang Zheng 1]] | launch_site = [[Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center|Jiuquan]] [[Jiuquan Launch Area 2|LA-2]]
| last_contact = {{end-date|14 May 1970}} | decay_date =
| orbit_epoch = 24 January 2015, 01:39:49&nbsp;UTC<ref name="n2yo">{{cite web|url=http://www.n2yo.com/satellite/?s=4382|title=DFH-1 Satellite details 1970-034A NORAD 4382|publisher=N2YO|date=24 January 2015|accessdate=25 January 2015}}</ref> | orbit_reference = [[geocentric orbit|Geocentric]] | orbit_regime = [[Medium Earth orbit|Medium Earth]] | orbit_periapsis = {{convert|442|km|mi}}<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_apoapsis = {{convert|2046|km|mi}}<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_inclination = 68.42&nbsp;degrees<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_semimajor = {{convert|7615.66|km|mi}}<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_eccentricity = 0.1053251<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_period = 110.24&nbsp;minutes<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_RAAN = 199.11&nbsp;degrees<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_arg_periapsis = 98.23&nbsp;degrees<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_mean_anomaly = 13.06&nbsp;degrees<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_mean_motion = 13.06<ref name="n2yo"/> | orbit_rev_number = 10,099<ref name="n2yo"/> | apsis = gee }}
'''''Dongfanghong I''''' ({{zh|s=东方红一号|t=東方紅一號|p=Dōngfānghóng Yīhào|l=The East is Red 1}}) was the first space [[satellite]] of the [[People's Republic of China]] (PRC), launched successfully on 24 April 1970 as part of the PRC's [[Dong Fang Hong|Dongfanghong]] space satellite program. At {{convert|173|kg|lbs|abbr=on}}, it was heavier than the first satellites of other countries. The satellite carried a [[radio transmitter]] which broadcast the song of the same name, ''Dōngfānghóng'' or "[[The East Is Red (song)|The East Is Red]]"; the broadcast lasted for 20 days while in orbit.
It was developed under the direction of [[Qian Xuesen]] ('''Tsien Hsue-shen'''), dean of the [[China Academy of Space Technology|Chinese Academy of Space Technology (CAST)]]. At the time, a total of five identical satellites were created. The first satellite launched successfully. The academy formulated a "Three-Satellite Plan" consisting of ''Dongfanghong I'', re-entry satellites, and [[geosynchronous orbit]] [[communications satellite]]s. [[Sun Jia-Dong]] was responsible for the ''Dongfanghong I'' technology. In 1967, [[Dang Hongxin]] chose a copper antenna membrane that resolved the difficulties of broadcasting on an ultra-short wave antenna between 100&nbsp;°C and −100&nbsp;°C. Engineers installed a music player playing "The East is Red" on the satellite.
== Launch == [[File:Dongfanghong-1.ogg|thumb|''Dongfanghong I'' broadcasting "[[The East is Red (song)|East is Red]]" and telemetry data]] While ''Dongfanghong I'' was transported to the launch site by train, armed guards were placed between every two electricity poles. On 24 April 1970 at 9:35 pm, a [[Long March rocket|Long March I rocket]] (CZ-1) lifted off from the [[Jiuquan Satellite Launch Center]], placing the ''Dongfanghong I'' satellite in orbit at 9:48 pm.{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}
== Objectives == The primary purpose of the ''Dongfanghong I'' satellite was to perform tests of satellite technology and take readings of the ionosphere and atmosphere.{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}
== Satellite design == The satellite was similar in shape to a symmetrical 72-faced polyhedron, had a mass of 173&nbsp;kg (381&nbsp;lb), and had a diameter of approximately one meter (39&nbsp;in). It spun 120 times per minute for stabilization. The outer surface was coated with a processed aluminum alloy for temperature control. The main body of the sphere had four ultrashortwave whip antennas of at least two meters (6½ ft) in length. The lower section was connected to a stage containing a rocket motor. It had a shiny metallic ring added to the bottom, with brightness magnitude from +5 to +8.{{Citation needed|date=February 2016}}
== Orbit == The satellite remains in orbit; as of {{Orbit|epoch|24 January 2015}} it was in an orbit with a [[apsis|perigee]] of {{convert|{{Orbit|perigee|442}}|km|mi}}, an [[apsis|apogee]] of {{convert|{{Orbit|apogee|2046}}|km|mi}} and [[orbital inclination|inclination]] of {{Orbit|inclination|68.42}}&nbsp;degrees.{{Orbit|ref|<ref name="n2yo"/>}} This near-earth elliptical orbit was 114.09 minutes per orbit. It has [[Satellite Catalog Number]] 4382 and [[International Designator]] 1970-034A.<ref name="satcat">{{cite web|url=http://planet4589.org/space/log/satcat.txt|title=Satellite Catalog|first=Jonathan|last=McDowell|work=Jonathan's Space Page|accessdate=13 December 2013}}</ref>
''Dongfanghong I'' had a design life of 20 days. During that time, it transmitted telemetry data and space readings to the Earth. On 14 May, its signal stopped.
== Reaction == With the successful launch of ''Dongfanghong I'', China became the fifth country after the Soviet Union, United States, France, and Japan to independently launch a satellite. Although ''Dongfanghong I'' was launched 13 years after ''[[Sputnik I]]'', its mass exceeded the combined masses of the first satellites of the other four countries. After this launch, Qian Xuesen proposed to the Chinese government that China should develop a manned space program and submitted a manned space undertaking report. [[Mao Zedong]] himself signed "approved" to the report.{{citation needed|date=August 2012}}
On 21 April 2005, the Chinese Academy of Space Technology gathered the science and technology personnel who participated in the design, manufacture, production, and supervision of ''Dongfanghong I''. The birthplace of ''Dongfanghong I'', the Beijing Satellite Manufacturing Plant, was used as a monument. The manufacturing plant, in coordination with the [[Shenzhou 5]] manned spacecraft anniversary, created a 1:1 scale replica of the ''Dongfanghong I'' satellite. It was exhibited in the Beijing Planetarium.
==See also== {{Portal|Spaceflight|China}} * [[Dong Fang Hong 02|Dongfanghong II]] * [[Timeline of artificial satellites and space probes]]
