{{Solar terms}}
The traditional East Asian calendars divide a year into 24 [[solar term]]s. '''''Xiǎomǎn''''', ''Shōman'', ''Soman'', or ''Tiểu mãn'' is the 8th solar term. It begins when the Sun reaches the [[celestial longitude]] of 60° and ends when it reaches the longitude of 75°. It more often refers in particular to the day when the Sun is exactly at the celestial longitude of 60°. In the [[Gregorian calendar]], it usually begins around 21 May and ends around 5 June (6 June East Asia time).

